# graph-database Best Practices

## Code Organization and Structure

### Use Explicit Node Labels and Relationship Types
Always define explicit node labels and relationship types to maintain clarity and enforce schema. This practice aids in understanding the data model at a glance.

❌ BAD
```cypher
MATCH (a)-[r]->(b) RETURN a, r, b
```

✅ GOOD
```cypher
MATCH (p:Person)-[f:FOLLOWS]->(f:Person) RETURN p, f
```

### Centralized Schema Management
Utilize `GRAPH TYPE` for centralized schema management. This ensures consistency across your graph database and makes it easier to manage changes.

```cypher
CREATE CONSTRAINT ON (p:Person) ASSERT p.id IS UNIQUE;
```

## Common Patterns and Anti-patterns

### Use MERGE for Idempotency
To avoid creating duplicate entities, always use `MERGE` with unique constraints.

❌ BAD
```cypher
CREATE (p:Person {id: '123', name: 'Alice'});
```

✅ GOOD
```cypher
MERGE (p:Person {id: '123'}) SET p.name = 'Alice';
```

### Avoid Unanchored Queries
Always anchor your queries on indexed properties to improve performance.

❌ BAD
```cypher
MATCH (p:Person) RETURN p;
```

✅ GOOD
```cypher
MATCH (p:Person {id: $userId}) RETURN p;
```

## Performance Considerations

### Use LIMIT for High-Fanout Traversals
When traversing relationships with high fan-out, always use `LIMIT` to prevent overwhelming your application with data.

❌ BAD
```cypher
MATCH (p:Person)-[:FOLLOWS]->(f:Person) RETURN f;
```

✅ GOOD
```cypher
MATCH (p:Person)-[:FOLLOWS]->(f:Person)
WITH f
LIMIT 100
RETURN f { .name, .email };
```

### Profile Your Queries
Utilize the `PROFILE` command to identify performance bottlenecks. This helps you optimize your queries effectively.

```cypher
PROFILE MATCH (p:Person)-[:FOLLOWS]->(f:Person) RETURN f;
```

## Common Pitfalls and Gotchas

### Avoid Heavy Payloads in Relationships
Keep relationship properties lightweight. Store heavy payloads directly on nodes to optimize performance.

❌ BAD
```cypher
CREATE (p:Person)-[:FOLLOWS {data: largePayload}]-(f:Person);
```

✅ GOOD
```cypher
CREATE (p:Person)-[:FOLLOWS]->(f:Person);
SET f.largeData = largePayload;
```

## Security Best Practices

### Use Parameters for Queries
Always use parameters to prevent injection attacks and enhance caching.

```cypher
MATCH (p:Person {id: $userId}) RETURN p;
```

## Query Optimization

### Use WITH for Intermediate Results
Utilize `WITH` to narrow down your result set between stages of complex queries.

❌ BAD
```cypher
MATCH (p:Person)-[:FOLLOWS]->(f:Person) RETURN f;
```

✅ GOOD
```cypher
MATCH (p:Person)-[:FOLLOWS]->(f:Person)
WITH f
RETURN f { .name, .email };
```

## Data Modeling

### Follow Traversal Paths, Not Tables
Design your data model based on traversal paths rather than relational tables. This aligns with how graph databases are optimized for queries.

```cypher
MATCH (p:Person)-[:FOLLOWS]->(f:Person)-[:LIKES]->(m:Movie)
RETURN f, m;
```

## Error Handling

### Handle Errors Gracefully
Always anticipate potential errors in your queries and handle them gracefully to avoid application crashes.

```cypher
WITH $userId AS userId
MATCH (p:Person {id: userId})
RETURN p
UNION
MATCH (p:Person)
WHERE NOT EXISTS((p)-[:FOLLOWS]->())
RETURN p;
```

By following these best practices, you can ensure that your graph-database applications are performant, secure, and maintainable. Always prioritize clarity in your data models and queries to facilitate easier debugging and future development.